## 📚 Layered Architecture & Assembly Definitions

To prevent circular dependencies and tangled code, the codebase is divided into **strict layers**.

A layer is conceptual, but enforced physically using:

> **Unity Assembly Definitions (`.asmdef`)**

Each layer contains multiple **Systems**, and:

> **Each System must have its own Assembly Definition**

---

### 🧱 Layer Hierarchy

```
┌──────────────────────────────┐
│ High Layer     (Gameplay)    │
│ Controllers • AI • Weapons   │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Mid Layer      (Features)    │
│ Inventory • UI • Quests      │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Low Layer      (Core)        │
│ Save • Audio • Input • Events│
└──────────────────────────────┘
```

- **High Layer (Gameplay):** Character Controllers, AI, Weapons, Game Modes  
- **Mid Layer (Features):** Inventory, Quest Log, UI Logic, Objectives  
- **Low Layer (Core Engine):** Save System, Audio, Localization, Input, Event Bus  

> [!TIP]
> This hierarchy is flexible. Add or adjust layers depending on project scale.

---

### 🚧 Dependency Rule — *The Iron Wall*

> Code can only reference:
> - Its own layer  
> - Layers **below**

---

> [!CAUTION]
> **Lower layers must NEVER reference higher layers.**  
>
> ❌ `Core.Audio` → `Gameplay.Weapons`  
> ✅ `Gameplay.Weapons` → `Core.Audio`  
>
> If a Core system needs Gameplay data, it must listen via the **Event Bus**.

